                    <div style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size:16px;line-height:25.6px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px;box-sizing:border-box;">
<figure style="width: 100%;padding-bottom:16px;text-align:left;margin:0">


                        <a href="https://techcabal.com/category/newsletters/tc-daily/">
                             <img decoding="async" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/06/cat-driving-serious.gif" width="100%" height="auto" style="object-fit: cover"></a>
                        <figcaption style="color:#808080;font-size:12px;font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;line-height:19.8px;padding-top:6px;font-weight:400">Image: Tenor</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                        
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">For a company that seems to spend half its time arguing with regulators, Starlink is having a pretty good run in Africa.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>What happened?</strong> Starlink has <a href="https://www.ecofinagency.com/news-digital/1506-56465-starlink-enters-cote-d-ivoires-satellite-internet-market-challenging-mtn-and-orange"style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">secured the licences</a> it needs to begin operations in C&ocirc;te d&#8217;Ivoire, where it will offer satellite internet services via its network of low Earth orbit satellites. The satellite internet provider will launch in C&ocirc;te d&#8217;Ivoire in July, making the country its 27th African market.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>What makes this different?</strong> Unlike many of Starlink&#8217;s earlier African launches, C&ocirc;te d&#8217;Ivoire is not a market waiting for its first serious satellite internet provider. In countries like Nigeria, Starlink entered some African markets where satellite internet was expensive or not widely available to consumers. C&ocirc;te d&#8217;Ivoire is different.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">Here, Starlink will go head-to-head with <a href="https://spaceinafrica.com/2026/04/27/eutelsat-mtn-cote-divoire-partner-to-expand-nationwide-satellite-broadband/"style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">MTN</a> and <a href="https://www.connectingafrica.com/connectivity/orange-c-te-d-ivoire-eutelsat-launch-satellite-broadband-services"style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">Orange</a>, two telecom giants that already offer satellite and hybrid connectivity services through a partnership with Eutelsat. In addition to introducing its technology, Starlink will attempt to convince customers to switch from providers they already know and use.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>There&#8217;s another challenge:</strong> Starlink may have trouble convincing customers to pay for the hardware or kits. In 2025, Starlink&#8217;s <a href="https://techcabal.com/2025/12/09/starlink-cost-africa-vs-others/"style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">Standard Kits cost</a> about $406.83 in Nigeria and $386.07 in Kenya. To put that into perspective, C&ocirc;te d&#8217;Ivoire&#8217;s monthly minimum wage for non-agricultural workers is about <a href="https://wage.is/ivory-coast/"style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">$132.85</a>. For many households, buying a Starlink kit could cost nearly three months&#8217; wages before they even pay for a subscription.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">It&#8217;s a challenge the company has encountered elsewhere. In Kenya, the company <a href="https://techcabal.com/2026/01/15/starlink-now-lets-kenya-pay-installments/"style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">introduced flexible payment plans</a> and rental options to lower the upfront cost of joining the network. C&ocirc;te d&#8217;Ivoire may present a similar test.</p>
<div id="share_content" style="width: 100%; background-color: transparent;box-sizing:border-box;">
                        <div style="display: table; width: 100%;">
                            <div style="display: table-cell; vertical-align:middle; text-align: left;">
                                  <a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://techcabal.com/category/newsletters/tc-daily/" rel="noopener" style="display:inline;width:24px;height:24px;background-color:#eeeeee;text-align:center;vertical-align: middle;border-radius:2px;padding:5px;margin-right: 10px;"><img decoding="async" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2023/05/Twitter.png" alt="" width="16px" height="auto" style="vertical-align: middle;"></a>
